{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This entry include parvins from mammals and paralysed arrest at two-fold protein 6 (pat-6) from C. elegans. Parvins and pat-6 contain an actin-binding domain (ABD) that consists of two in tandem arranged calponin homology (CH) domains. The ABD domain enables parvins to recruit F-actin to focal adhesions and associate with stress fibres [[cite:PUB00068389]]. Parvins bind to actin binding/regulatory proteins and co-localise with integrins [[cite:PUB00068389]]. Therefore, they may be involved in integrin-mediated adhesion and actin-dependent processes such as cell shape regulation and cell migration [[cite:PUB00068389]].</p>\n\n<p>In humans, there are three parvins. Alpha-parvin (also known as actopaxin/CH-ILKBP) is ubiquitously expressed and is required for normal development of the embryonic cardiovascular system [[cite:PUB00068389], [cite:PUB00068392]]. Beta-parvin (also known as affixin) is enriched in heart and skeletal muscle [[cite:PUB00068391]]. The expression of gamma-parvin (gamma-pv) is restricted to haematopoietic cells and plays a subtle role for blood cell homeostasis [[cite:PUB00068393]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "2vzc", "name" "Crystal structure of the C-terminal calponin homology domain of alpha parvin"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036872", "name" "CH domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"pirsf" {"PIRSF039131" "Alpha/beta/gamma-parvin"}, "panther" {"PTHR12114" "PARVIN"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Parvin", "short" "Parvin"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 12, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 1017, "taxa" 5772, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 5385, "sets" 0, "proteins" 5113, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 2808}, "pathways" 11}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR0